almost stepped on nesting female while walking off the Amazon Villas road to look for a WBTF. Female sat completely still as I took pictures a few inches from her face. Nest was well-concealed enough that I did not find it upon looking back a few times in the next few weeks. Joe, however, on the 22nd of August, found an egg shell at the site, which I kept, indicating that the nest must have been there the whole time.

Observation Details: Staying on the trees.

The kites were observed foraging on a large, winged hymenopteran (ants or termites) that were swarming above the lodge at Hacienda Concepcion. Two photos here show the kites actively eating the abdomens, after which they dropped the remaining parts of the insects (head and thorax) to the ground. We noticed numerous individual insects crawling on the ground without abdomens. The swifts were also likely foraging on these insects, but they likely ate the entire insect whole.
A pair of adults. Photos by all. Responded to playback. Also an old nest in a cactus.

Observation Details: Six individual, standing close together between the whimbrels and the willets in the shallow parts of the lagoon. Much smaller than either whimbrel or willet, with relatively long legs and a long, slightly decurved bill. Most of them showed a rufous patch on the cheeks, as is typical for the breeding plumage of this species. Stilt sandpiper is known to stay well into May, until the last individuals head north to their breeding areas.

Locality: Refugio de Vida Silvestre Los Pantanos de Villa
Observation Details: Individuo solitario. ¿juvenil o adulto en muda?. Fue observado a las 9:46 am flotando cerca de la totora de la laguna Marvilla. Podría haber pasado desapercibido. Una fulica ardesiaca muy territorial lo espantó y lo hizo mas visible. Se juntó con un grupo de Phalaropus tricolor. Se mantuvo alrededor de 30 minutos a 1 o 2 metros de la orilla. Pudo observarse comportamientos de alimentación y limpieza. En ese intervalo de tiempo fue posible verificar el registro de la especie y tomar fotografías. La observación se prolongó hasta las 10:21 am.

Observation Details: What I wrote on Instagram: "While winding our way through the jungle towards the clay lick, we heard a few macaws. Sensing a good photo opportunity, we quietly worked our way towards the blind. There were two Red-and-green Macaws (Ara chloropterus) present, but they were somewhat obscured by leaves. ⠀ ⠀ Expecting that this was our best photo opportunity, we laid down on the benches and pointed our lenses through the very small openings in the blind. I was laying horizontally with my head dangling off the bench - it was very uncomfortable! We got decent photos, good ones to hold onto for memories and to share with friends and family. ⠀ ⠀ But a short time later, another macaw flew in, followed by another. And these birds were in the trees, out in the open, and much closer to us. To make things even better, the sun started to break through the clouds...and another small group of macaws flew in. ⠀

2 - at noonish walking back down road to taxi I heard some bird noises coming from under tall trees at roadside. I walked in and stood in the shade for some time looking at movement. After being there for some time a jay flew in quite close. We both were startled I think and it moved off fairly quickly but a good look. I stayed around and another came in 10 minutes later and started foraging on ground. I watched for awhile and then moved closer for a pic. It flew up to eye level and watched me for awhile as I took some pictures. Good look at a nice bird.

It made us wonder whether these birds bread on the cliffs, but we did not see any specific breading behavior.

Observation Details: Individuo solitario. ¿juvenil o adulto en muda?. Fue observado a las 9:46 am flotando cerca de la totora de la laguna Marvilla. Podría haber pasado desapercibido. Una fulica ardesiaca muy territorial lo espantó y lo hizo mas visible. Se juntó con un grupo de Phalaropus tricolor. Se mantuvo alrededor de 30 minutos a 1 o 2 metros de la orilla. Pudo observarse comportamientos de alimentación y limpieza. En ese intervalo de tiempo fue posible verificar el registro de la especie y tomar fotografías. La observación se prolongó hasta las 10:21 am.

Fernando says "It’s the migratory one, tundrius, probably a male. The cassini has very closed “hood”, almost no “moustache” noticeable. Also, tundrius is very white on the breast, cassini creamy." Thanks Fernando for the feedback.

Pair(s). Heard(s) and seen. Subspecies and/or taxon identified by size, shape, color pattern and/or sound. Male had a complete solid black cap surrounding the ear patch giving the cap a pointy claw-shape look to the corners at the sides of the neck, slaty back, whitish below, with grayish chest sides, black wings with inner white-webbed flight feathers, black short pointy bill and black tail with prominent white outer tail feathers. Female quite similar to male in overall plumage except by the narrow somewhat broken white spectacles (just to over the eye) joining with whitish lores and supraloral stripe. The bird was first heard at the higher parts of the scrubby slope, later on after use of PB, birds responded immediately and came quite close on exposed branches to investigate, and then both began foraging nearby on small bushes on lower part of the slope, making contact calls. Habitat: Pacific arid scrub with scattered cactus. Bird heard first at ca. 09:40hrs. and pair last heard and seen by 10:45hrs. Elevation ca. 2300 m. Audio recorded. (recordings after PB, and natural vocalizations). *Literature ("All the Birds of the World" book published by Lynx Edicions - Josep del Hoyo (Editor)) shows that female of Polioptila maior has a white narrow forehead which joins with white broken spectacles, which is the only noticeable difference with the female shown in the picture(s) taken by some members in the group, where the female has black forehead concolor with cap. These difference rise questions: Maybe a different subspecies isolated by geographic barriers or a hybrid between 2 taxa?.

Observation Details: This is a tough ID. The bird was flushed up the hillside and was about 150 m up slope. The sun was very bright potentially washing out contrast and colors. Either A. albicauda or A. montanus. Though A. montanus was seen during the day, there were no other Agriornis to compare with this individual.     Field marks consistent with A. albicauda - heavy bill with distinct hook, white/pale lower mandible, clear white throat with distinct dark streaking  Field marks consistent with A. montanus- limited streaking on breast and flanks, little contrast between throat and upper breast    A. montanus is expected to have an all dark lower mandible or at least an all dark base and indistinct throat streaking without contrast between white-throat and breast. Both these traits are not apparent in the picture. Still, the picture does not exhibit as much streaking on lower parts (breast, flanks) as depicted for A.albicauda in Schulenberg or in the LSUMNS collections and it does not have a sharp contrast between white throat and brownish belly.     In balance, the field marks pointing to A. montanus could be greatly affected by the lighting conditions of the bird whereas the color and heft of the bill, and contrasting throat streaking are not expected to be influence by lighting conditions as much. Given this, I believe this individual o be A. albicauda.

Media notes: Two nestlings.
Observation Details: Heard(s) and seen. Pair(s) feeding young (02) at nest. Both adult(s) were foraging on ground and cacti coming in and out of the nest bringing food to young from ca. 08:00hrs. to ca. 11:30hrs. Carrying fecal sacs out of the nest by ca. 10:30hrs. and 10:50hrs. Nest site at ca. 1580 m altitude and the cacti it was on belongs to the species Haageocereus pseudomelanostele it was about 2 m tall. Some of the recognizable arthropods the adults were catching to feed their young were a spider and a stick insect. With picture(s) and audio recorded.
